    {
      "title": "Orbit Basics: Speed vs Height",
      "description": "Build intuition for circular orbit speed, escape speed, and gravity at altitude around a simple spherical planet.",
      "markdown": "# Orbit Basics: Speed vs Height\n\nThis scene introduces the three key quantities that control orbital insertion:\n\n$$g(r)=\\frac{\\mu}{r^2}, \\qquad v_{\\text{circ}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\mu}{r}}, \\qquad v_{\\text{esc}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{2\\mu}{r}}$$\n\nwhere:\n- $r=R_p+h$ is distance from planet center (planet radius plus altitude),\n- $\\mu=GM$ is the gravitational parameter.\n\nIn the sliders, we use scaled values:\n- $G_s = G\\times 10^{11}$\n- $M_x = M/10^{24}$\n- so $\\mu = G_s\\,M_x\\times10^4$ in km$^3$/s$^2$.\n\n## What To Look For\n\n1. As altitude $h$ increases, both $v_{\\text{circ}}$ and $v_{\\text{esc}}$ decrease.\n2. Gravity weakens with $1/r^2$, but it never becomes zero.\n3. Orbital insertion is mostly a **sideways speed problem**: you need enough tangential speed at the chosen altitude.\n\n## Earth Reference (for context)\n\nUsing Earth-like values $R_p\\approx 6371\\,\\text{km}$ and $\\mu\\approx 398600\\,\\text{km}^3/\\text{s}^2$, low Earth orbit speeds are around $7.8\\,\\text{km/s}$ and escape speed near the surface is about $11.2\\,\\text{km/s}$.\n\nThese values match standard educational and agency references (NASA).",
      "prompt": "Teach orbital insertion as speed-height-energy tradeoffs. Emphasize that altitude alone does not make orbit; tangential speed is essential. Keep formulas tied to the live sliders.",
